ADR-0006 — Runtime Planning Pipeline
Status: Accepted
Date: 2026-07-19
Context
The Runtime must transform business intentions into executable workflows while remaining completely independent of the Company domain.
Historically, planning, workflow construction and execution tend to become tightly coupled. This makes systems difficult to evolve and nearly impossible to replace individual components.
Pharos adopts a layered planning pipeline where each stage has exactly one responsibility.
Decision
The Runtime planning pipeline is defined as:
CompanyIntent
        │
        ▼
(ACL Adapter)
        │
        ▼
RuntimeIntent
        │
        ▼
PlanningRequest
        │
        ▼
RuntimePlanner
        │
        ▼
PlanningResult
        │
        ▼
RuntimePlan
        │
        ▼
WorkflowBuilder
        │
        ▼
Workflow
        │
        ▼
ExecutionStrategy
        │
        ▼
Runtime
Responsibilities
CompanyIntent
Represents a business objective.
Examples:
Release version 2.0
Audit localization
Analyze repository
Generate documentation
It belongs exclusively to Company.
RuntimeIntent
Represents the Runtime's understanding of that objective.
Runtime does not know anything about Company.
PlanningRequest
Container passed into the planner.
It carries the RuntimeIntent.
Nothing more.
RuntimePlanner
Responsible for deciding what plan should be produced.
It does not execute anything.
It does not create workflows.
It does not call tools.
PlanningResult
Represents the output of planning.
Today it contains:
RuntimePlan
It may later include metadata, diagnostics, confidence, or reasoning.
RuntimePlan
Represents the high-level execution blueprint.
A RuntimePlan describes what must happen.
It does not describe how execution occurs.
WorkflowBuilder
Transforms a RuntimePlan into a Workflow.
Responsible only for workflow construction.
Workflow
Represents executable steps.
No planning logic exists here.
ExecutionStrategy
Responsible for execution order.
Examples:
Sequential
Parallel
Conditional
Retry
Human approval
Runtime
Executes workflows.
Nothing more.
Architectural Principles
Every layer owns exactly one responsibility.
Information flows downward.
Execution never flows upward.
Planning never depends on execution.
Execution never depends on Company.
Dependency Rules
Company must never import Runtime.
Runtime must never import Company.
Workflow must never know Planning.
Planning must never know Workflow internals.
Execution must never modify Plans.
Benefits
The pipeline allows:
alternative planners
multiple workflow builders
multiple execution engines
deterministic testing
AI-assisted planning
future distributed execution
without changing the surrounding layers.
Consequences
Adding a new planner requires no Runtime changes.
Replacing execution strategies requires no planning changes.
Company can evolve independently.
Runtime can be embedded into different products.
